Good Morning. We’re Team Pantheon, and today we’ll be presenting the alpha version of our software. Pantheon is a software system designed for code similarity detection and plagiarism analysis within academic programming environments. 


*Share screen of the main website*


Pantheon uses role-based access, so users can log in either as a student or an instructor. For this example, we are logging in as a student.

To access the system, the student enters their email, password, and an assignment key that is provided by the instructor. The assignment key links the student’s submission to a specific assignment in the system.

Once the student signs in, the system verifies their credentials and redirects them to the assignment submission interface, where they can upload their programming work. Our engine developers have designed the engine so that the software will accept Java, C++, and C coding languages. 

Once submissions are uploaded, Pantheon processes the source code through its comparison engine, where the files are tokenized and structurally analyzed to generate similarity scores between different student submissions. After following up on that, I will be showing you the instructor's point of view, where you will see the comparison scores.

After logging in, the instructor is taken to the Pantheon dashboard, which serves as the main control interface for managing courses and assignments.

At the top, the instructor can view their registered courses. Each course acts as a container that organizes assignments and student submissions.

Within each course, the instructor can create new assignments. Each assignment generates a unique assignment key, which is shared with students so their submissions can be correctly linked to that assignment.

Here we can see an example assignment listed under the course. The instructor can select Review, which allows them to analyze submitted code and view the similarity results generated by the Pantheon comparison engine.

The dashboard also allows instructors to create additional courses or assignments, giving them full control over how submissions are organized and evaluated within the system


